<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-strict.dtd">
<html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    <head>
        <title>CSS Test: Offsets for relatively position children are ignored for block-level non-replaced elements in normal flow when overflow does not compute to visible</title>
        <link rel="author" title="Microsoft" href="http://www.microsoft.com/" />
        <link rel="help" href="http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS21/visudet.html#normal-block" />
        <meta name="flags" content="" />
        <meta name="assert" content="Verify that relatively positioned children are considered without their offsets. When a block-level non-replaced element is in normal flow and overflow does not compute to visible but has been propagated to the viewport." />
        <style type="text/css">
            html, body
            {
                overflow: scroll;
            }
            #d1
            {
                position: relative;
            }
            #d2
            {
                border: 3px solid red;
                width: 300px;
            }
            #d3
            {
                position: relative;
                top: 50px;
                left: 150px;
                height: 100px;
            }
            #d4
            {
                position: absolute;
                top: 0;
                border: 3px solid green;
                height: 100px;
                width: 300px;
            }
        </style>
    </head>
    <body>
        <p>Test passes if there is no red visible on the page.</p>
        <div id="d1">
            <div id="d2">
                <div id="d3">
                </div>
            </div>
            <div id="d4"></div>
        </div>
    </body>
</html>